text:

The server said the plates are meant to be shared, so we ordered more dishes than we originally intended to. But when you order a plate for $45 and only get three Brussels sprouts to ‚Äúshare,‚Äù you feel robbed. After spending more $200 total, we were not even full when we left.

title: Lucian Books and Wine
text:
Walked in to treat myself to a nice cocktail and a small bite. The look of the restaurant is beautiful and intimate. Great for a drink at the bar with a book or for a date. I sat at the bar and the bartender was very helpful with recommending a cocktail and food. She suggested a delicious yuzu cocktail that I had with an amazing custard dessert that was decorated with glazed pears and other fruit.
I enjoyed sitting at the bar and talking with the staff who were very helpful on recommending great dishes and delivering excellent service.

title: Lucian Books and Wine
text:
I‚Äôve been here for lunch and dinner. Google restricts my review to one meal (at least for photos and menu items) but I‚Äôd love to share my experiences of both.

My latest visit was for lunch. This is one of the most underrated lunch experiences in Atlanta. The atmosphere is light, airy, casual but elevated/sophisticated. Menu seems unassuming but has some absolute knockouts. Service was also just really enjoyable; I‚Äôm not much of a conversationalist but had Caroline at the bar and ended up having one of the best restaurant chats in recent memory, and was guided through the menu for an awesome selection of the omelette, sticky toffee pudding, and coffee.

Dinners are more intimate, and a little hard to get a reservation so it‚Äôs been tough for my schedule. Unsure how a group reservation would go but can vouch for solo trips and dates, or close 1:1 catch ups. Despite the reservation struggles, I appreciate the smaller seating capacity and streamlined menu. I suppose I‚Äôd like more small bite options to pair with the wine because I always end up getting the Jam√≥n Ib√©rico and would like more meats, but that‚Äôs knit pick.

I‚Äôll end with a confirmation that the book store element is not a gimmick and not aesthetics only - the curation is so well done. I‚Äôve gotten 5 books as gifts and 2 for myself.

Really appreciate this spot. Atlanta could use more spaces like this that execute on the actual food experience as well as they do in the creativity and vibe.

title: Lucian Books and Wine
text: Couldn‚Äôt ask for a better experience. The atmosphere is beautiful, the menu has everything you could ever want, and the service is wonderful - everyone is so knowledgeable and kind. Highly recommend treating yourself to lunch service at the bar!

title: WIN - Taste of Bali
text: A beautiful restaurant with absolutely wonderful food and attentive service. We have been going to WIN for a number of years and have always enjoyed our experience and meals. Over the years the menu has changed but the quality of the food has remained consistently high, delicious, and interesting. They offer wonderful coffees and delicious drinks, the Kuno Fashioned being a must try!

title: WIN - Taste of Bali
text:
Had dinner there the other night; no reservation but was promptly seated. The atmosphere is very nice, and the music selection was good for me, as it was mainly 90s and early 00s. It was also played at a nice, audible-but-not-intrusive level. My partner and I could easily hear each other talk. The service was great, and our server was very patient and knowledgeable about the whole menu. He also gave good recommendations.
The food was amazing. Best tofu I've had in years. The duck was great, and the corn fritters were good. All the fried foods were light, not greasy and heavy, and tasted like they used clean oil. The drinks were good, and reasonably priced. Actually, everything was reasonably priced because we had about 10 things and the bill was on par for a business lunch for us, even though it was a nice dinner.

We will definitely be back soon.

title: WIN - Taste of Bali
text:
Planned to meet with a group and some members of our party arrived much later than planned. Regardless, the service was excellent, food and drinks were prompt and excellent.

For the appetizer, we had the small tasting plate with corn fritters, kreme crispy chicken and pork wonton. The crispy chicken was my favorite, it was crunchy and still juicy, just perfection. The shrimp crackers they give are also really good along with the sauce. For the mains there was a mixture of lamb, beef and chicken ordered and everyone enjoyed their meals and accompanying drinks.

title: WIN - Taste of Bali

It wasn‚Äôt busy yet our order was delayed, any seared pieces that would have been great if they were ‚Äújust seared‚Äù were now room temp; better quality than your average sushi spot, but not high end, and not worth going all out. title: Brush Sushi
text:
Had a wonderful experience here. We had 16 course omakase tasting, and added few additional pieces right before desserts. Every single course was beautiful and delicious. Especially the design of plates/objets went perfect with each piece. For some of them, I felt like I was looking an contemporary art! Chef was super professional(Sorry I forgot to ask your name, you were the best) and provided enough(but not too complicated) explanations for us.

For drinks, welcome drink was amazing lovely. Crafted cocktail was bit strong and too flavourful to me. Not balanced. I also ordered sake flights, which was the best choice. Portion of sake was not much, nor
little. Server explained/recommended each sake and told us which sake would go well for each dish. We told them we're celebrating PHD defense, and they put small congrats graduate decor for our dessert. Gift after the course was also quite impressive - a sweet treat and teabag. We had to wait about 20 minutes because other people came late, but I was not angry as the chef/server explained and apologized enough.

Overall satisfied. Definitely will come again to try 25 course.

title: Brush Sushi
text: My wife and I came to brush for dinner after our wedding. We were excited to try the tasting menu and it did not disappoint. The rice in each roll and nigiri was amazing, the fish fresh and buttery, the service was exceptional and they treated us so well. We really enjoyed our wedding dinner here. Thank you to Brush for making our meal so memorable.

title: Brush Sushi
text:
Having tried thoroughly enjoyed our omakase experiences at Mujo and Hiyakawa we have been trying to find other similar experiences in Atlanta. I am happy to report that Brush's omakase did not disappoint. The service was outstanding. Both the servers and the chef spent generous amounts of time talking with us and making sure we had everything we needed/wanted.

We did the 16 course menu and it was the perfect amount a food and I would say it is a better value when compared to Mujo or Hiyakawa. I would say the atmosphere sits in between those two. Mujo having a very chill comfortable vibe and Hiyakawa being more like a museum and culinary course. At Brush you get a more chill vibe and can get as little or as much information you want to the meal. I would also say that Brush is much less overbearing on the rules than either Mujo and Hiyakawa which was very nice.

The quality of the fish and dishes were amazing. Brush has a unique rice and some unique presentations that the other places don't have. All things considered I think Brush my be the best overall place (accounting for price, comfort and experience).

The only draw back of the omakase experience for me is the the space in not an intimate as the other spots I have mentioned. You can definitely tell you are in Buckhead.

title: Brush Sushi

title: Brush Sushi
text: Very excellent sushi. I feel bad for saying this as a loyal Umi, Tomo's and MF Sushi fan. This is an elegant touch above. You have to savor each bite. If you want to lavish your taste buds, try this experience.

title: Brush Sushi
text: Putting it mildly, we are foodie food snobs, and we had one of the best meals in a long time at Brush. We came for a special occasion and sat at the bar with Angel, who was a lovely guide to our meal and helped us choose some delicious sake. We began with the dry-aged fish tasting - fresh and delicious. Then we enjoyed both the caviar and o-toro service, both of which exceeded expectations. And finally we ordered the table side wagyu - meat-in-your-mouth delicious. We weren‚Äôt sure what to expect, and left satiated and delighted.

title: Brush Sushi
text:
Wow what an experience! From the hostess to the chef our experience was phenomenal. Went for the omakase experience and will be back for sure. We were greeted by a very kind hostess who took our coats and led us to the bar while we waited for our sever- the bar was attentive, quick and very friendly even offering suggestions based on our usual drink types. Our server came to greet us at the bar and walked us to the Omakase area which was so beautiful ‚Äî the details of the restaurant were just perfect.

Once we sat down our server went over the drink pairing with us and we opted to let him choose for us throughout the dinner (excellent decision). The chef came out to greet us and immediately started preparing fresh wasabi and getting right into the meal.

The food was delicious. They have a unique sushi experience with dry aging the fish. We were able to compare fresh and dry aged of multiple types and then moved on to Nigiri (and wow this was my favorite part). Everything we ate was delicious and we left very satisfied and will be back.

We didn‚Äôt take many photos as we were living in the moment but this place needs to be added to your must try date night spots ASAP.

First time in and trying arepas and although the taste of the yucca arepas is so unique that some may find it more interesting than delicious, I still enjoyed it. Probably more than the meal I enjoyed the customer service. They were freakishly kind for atlanta service standards. So personal, attentive, & warm‚Ä¶.which is probably the basis for my review. They have house made sauces, sandwich freebies, & vegan options.

I wished the portions were larger and there was a sign on building because without it you‚Äôll certainly miss it.

Overall do recommend

title: Phat Yuca
text:
Am I the only one who thinks of Bob‚Äôs Burgers when I visit this place?  The husband/wife team always find a way to mention the kids. There‚Äôs a tangible passion for the food. And there‚Äôs seldom a wait even though ‚ÄúPesto‚Äôs‚Äù next door is cranking out ‚Äújalape√±o poppers‚Äù to the masses.  All they need is an ‚Äúarepa of the day‚Äù board.

Now for the food ‚Ä¶. It‚Äôs delicious!!! And a little different from what you‚Äôll find anywhere else. My wife has celiac and is also vegan. She LOVES a dedicated gluten free facility with plenty of options.

title: Phat Yuca
text:
This is a place worth returning to eat at.  Having Celiac disease makes traveling and eating out safely quite difficult.   I also have a high sensitivity to gluten (my dog has to be gluten free) soI often suffer on trips.  My husband looks for places that st least indicate Gluten-free options.  Well,  this find is a gem.  Absolutely no issues after eating here.  Full but not the heavy feeling after eating a sandwich and the most deceptive gluten-free macaroni. We will be back.
(P.s.  owners amd staff being knowledgeable and friendly are just a bonus!)

title: Phat Yuca
text: I was so excited about trying this place, but unfortunately, I didn‚Äôt get the opportunity to. The woman behind the counter wouldn‚Äôt let me get a word in edgewise. I found her to be quite rude and condescending as she was explaining the menu, which I told her that I had already looked at online to familiarize myself with. Im already familiar with vegan cuisine, which I‚Äôve been eating and preparing since the 1980s. I feel like there‚Äôs a lot of cultural appropriation going on here and that‚Äôs not cool either but be that as it may, someone needs cultural/ethnic sensitivity training to go along with the food. The decor and space is nice and bright, a little awkwardly shaped but they seem to be making best of the space. Note to self: any time AAVE is being used in the menu and advertising, caveat emptor.

title: Phat Yuca
text:
I try to visit this place as often as I can for lunch or dinner, as my schedule allows! It is such a wonderful treat to have in the ATL area. Being able to eat here without the worry of allergen cross contamination AND have amazingly delicious food is a huge gift. The prices are reasonable considering all the considerations made for diets (they're dairy, nut, soy, and gluten free) and the menu has several options, including vegan options. Each item I have ordered has blown my socks off.

The indoor seating space is a little small, but there is also outdoor seating.

I highly recommend this place. I've taken a number of friends here just because I love this place so much. Try it out if you haven't! I really don't think you'll be disappointed. üôÇ

text: If you want over priced food go here. If you want overpriced drinks go here! After a night at the club we decided to keep the moment going. It‚Äôs 3:30 am on a Thursday night when I heard the lady said its $80 for entry (I actually chuckled and said to myself this is not Vegas ) however I was with a group who already had a section so I wasn‚Äôt worried about a price . The lady then claims that the  group inside already has the maximum amount of people in the section ( 4 ) and it will be extra for any additional people cool,  it was handled by the men we were with. Upon entry I was hit with a very foul smell, it literally smelled like sewage however once we went up into like this jungle blue area the smell was no more. Once we got to the section the drinks came and they were poured into Flask (I guess to prevent people from throwing the bottles idk why ) but heres the biggest red flag!  I could taste the alcohol and tell that this was not the brand actual liquor it‚Äôs fake version. I was actually shocked that such an established would try to deceive people . I guess they expect people to be too high to even notice lol but I was pissed although I wasn‚Äôt even the one paying. For  10 wings it cost $36 dollars the most I‚Äôve seen for wings since I‚Äôve to ATL . I do think this place needs be properly inspected though I saw some safety concerns such as the fabric on the roof,  in case of fire there was no sprinklers or perhaps the sprinklers are blocked by the fabric, also no proper ventilation and not a second exit.

text:
This is our one of the favorite Indian food restaurant in Atlanta and it‚Äôs on the top of the list. We come here to celebrate special occasions.

Yesterday, we ordered some dishes that we have never tried here before.

Kurkuri Bhindi was perfect and excellent.

Paneer Vindaloo was as expected spicy but we couldn‚Äôt stop eating it until it was finished.

We requested some food without onion and garlic (I know some of you will üò±) My wife doesn‚Äôt eat them and we were given couple of choices and she picked Paneer Saag and Daal Tadka. They were both good.

Masal soda Limca and Chilli mango mojito were spot on.

Why 4/5 stars? Roomali Roti was little less warm, almost on cold side and that makes it not so pleasant. Otherwise, everything else was perfect.

Staff is always at their best, making sure the guests feels they are special and satisfied.

Ambience and location draws us here over and over again.

Until next celebration, we will cherish this visit.

title: Pasta Vino
text:
This post was made solely for the sake of the desserts. Whoever you have back there in pastry are putting their hearts and souls into these sweets.

I enjoyed a pistachio cupcake, and my lover a tiramisu. I, upon biting into the middle of the cupcake, took a second to process whether or not this texture was real. The sponge was incredibly soft and fluffy, aerated and moist. The pistachio flavor was present, but subtle. Accompanied by what may have been the finest cream cheese icing I‚Äôve consumed in my life. Candied pistachio pieces scattered on top made for the finest delicacy I‚Äôve had in a while. Simple ‚Äî executed perfectly.

As for the tiramisu, I can‚Äôt say that I‚Äôve historically been a fan of them (too bitter), so my notes on them are notably less. My companion, upon first bite, immediately remarked that it was ‚Äúvery good‚Äù with the bite still in his mouth. I found it to be very soft and creamy, with a present but not too powerful taste of espresso. The ladyfingers were soft and crumbly; the whipped topping a cloud resting on my tongue. My only note is that the overall texture was very monotone. I think a crunchier ladyfinger would lend some liveliness to the dish.

But yes, phenomenal desserts that deserve a special review and shoutout! ‚ù§Ô∏è

text: If you live in Atlanta -- or visiting -- make time to reserve your spot at La Grotta, especially the outside patio. title: La Grotta Ristorante
text: I enjoyed dinner with my boyfriend at this clean and authentic establishment. However, the food itself was subpar, I fine dine frequently, most recently going to Malio‚Äôs in Tampa Florida. The escargot there was lovely as well as the one here  at la Grotta. But the burrata cheese lacked flavor, and the bread was rustic but yet again lacked flavor. The olive oil was served without any herbs or seasoning, which is fine, but it didn‚Äôt taste like a cold pressed olive oil so I was confused on why it was served so basic. Their wine list is insanely huge, and you would assume that you could find something for everyone. Unfortunately for me I like champagne, and they only have 2-3 champagne‚Äôs they sell by the glass and they are all bitter. So I had to settle with a moscato that wasn‚Äôt that good. My partner doesn‚Äôt too much care for wines, he‚Äôs more of a whiskey drinker. Although the establishment was beautiful, and the food was authentic I‚Äôm very disappointed in the initial experience me and my boyfriend had to face. Given the amount of time this establishment has been around I expected to be experiencing something better than Flemings but the food didn‚Äôt live up to the expectations. My waiter was absolutely amazing and gave great suggestions for our meals and desserts. He was attentive, funny , and accommodating to all of our requests. I hope to return in the future and to be greeted with a better, more tasteful experience at La Grotta.

title: Taqueria Del Sol
text:
Taqueria definition: a Mexican restaurant specializing in tacos.

As a mexican, I felt out of place at this taqueria because it is NOT AUTHENTIC. This is basically a locally owned On the Border / La Frontera Grill. The food isn't the worst but far from flavorful. Even the cashier said, "Were a boring Taqueria"

My husband hates these types of places because they profit/benefit from the name 'Taqueria' when the flavor/authenticity isn't there. It's cultural appropriation, but I'm sure it's okay since some of the workers were Hispanic, and 1 co-Founder is Mexican. But the main guy is Mike Klank, a white American. It saddens me that Mr. Hernandez has accepted to Americanize our Mexican culture for financial gain. It's altered to fit the demographic they're looking for. The same thing is happening in Mexico. I understand that, but its not right. Its white-washed.

Health inspection was an 86 B.
No onions or cilantro on the tacos.
Tacos are made with flour tortillas, not corn.
No salsa bar.
Enchilada is $4 each, and it looked like vomit. The chicken it had was rotisserie chicken.
Canned beer was $5 each.
Guac was the only decent thing there.

We took the food to go, adding a 5% fee.
We went to El Rey del Taco right after for real Mexican food.

Don't recommend and won't be back.

title: The Boiler Seafood Atlanta
text:
We visited The Boiler Seafood Atlanta on a Friday around 6:30 PM. Fortunately, our server was friendly and attentive. However, we were disappointed with the quality of the food. We ordered nearly all the appetizers, but none of them tasted fresh. It was as if they had been prepackaged and came straight from the freezer. For our main course, we ordered lobster bites with fried rice, two different boiler bags, and two orders of Alfredo pasta. Unfortunately, everything in the boiler bags and the fried rice was overcooked, and even the potatoes had sprouted and tasted terrible. When we complained about the taste of one of the boiler bags, they said they couldn't make another one but offered us a free cup of sauce to mask the sour taste. The two orders of Alfredo pasta looked completely different from each other. In one, the sauce was extremely thick, making it almost impossible to pull apart. In the other, the sauce was very watery and resembled soup.

Although the alcoholic drinks we ordered were tasty, they lacked alcohol. If you prefer drinks that are not overly sweet, avoid ordering them. The atmosphere was okay, but it wasn't suitable for families due to the constant hookah smoke and loud music. The parking lot is small, so valet parking is your best option.

title: Carmel
text: Starting with the positive ; staff was friendly and nice and the service was good  ‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶ Carmel might be the most contrived restaurant in Atlanta and it shows the minute you walk in .  The owner‚Äôs interpretation of ‚Äúa postcard to (from) ??? the coast ‚Äú feels like a 1980s Balkan‚Äôs cafeteria and is dim , sterile and oddly out of place . The cocktail menu is diverse but ask for details as the descriptions really don‚Äôt give a clear picture of what you are getting and we found the flavors to be just odd in three of them .  The wine by the glass is limited and overpriced . Food is divided into ‚Äúgems‚Äù second plates and main courses .  We decided to start off with about 5 plates to share .  The scallops were horrific and sliced horizontally in a milky broth that had no flavor ; a shrimp dish with peanuts was decent but weirdly presented with the heads detached from the tails and lined up on one side of the dish ‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶ We had three other items that were so unmemorable I have no idea what they were . We decided to skip ordering more and bailed around the corner to the Vietnamese restaurant bar for appetizers and drinks . I really don‚Äôt get Carmel at all , it‚Äôs schizophrenic in concept and food which makes it unsophisticated unpalatable and a hard pass in my opinion ‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶‚Ä¶your wallet will thank me too !

title: Bambinelli's Italian Restaurant
text: When our large family gathers we like to have sombeody else do the cooking. Lately that somebody has been Bambinelli's takeout. We love the basics here - Chicken and Eggplant Parm with a side of pasta, Calzones, Pizza, Lasagna and especially the large family salads. There is something for everybody on the menu. We gather up our orders and then send a runner over since we live next door in Garden Hills. But we have also used the delivery service and were pleased. We started doing this during the CoVid lockdown and it is one of the few good things to come out of that time. Instead of paying a small fortune to go to a Buckhead restaurant we get great food served with our own beverages around big table at home. Babies get put to bed on time, conversations around the table linger and there always seems to be enough food for leftovers. Bonnie Bambinelli would approve.  Bada Bing.

title: Grand China
text:
This was my first time and my last time dining here. Though to say that I "dined" is a gross understatement. Last night, I came here with my friends who had good things to say about this restaurant. We were greeted by the owner, who bragged about servicing Stevie Wonder, the Georgia Congressional Representatives, and all the positive reviews that her establishment has received. She even went so far as to say that her Egg Fu Young was highly rated by her New York customers. As a native New Yorker I was curious about the food. We were seated and placed our orders. Well, my dish was garnished with a hair smack dab in the middle of the plate. When I brought this to our server's attention, she was very apathetic and merely took the dish back. Her response made me scared to try anything else. So while my friends apparently had no issues with their food, I just sipped on the Coke that I ordered.

When it came time to pay the bill, she handed me mine with an attitude and let me know that she removed the dish from the bill, like she was doing me a big favor. Yet, she had no problem charging me $4.36 for a so, so glass of Coke. As we were leaving, the owner stopped us and asked if everything was okay, to which I responded no. She made no effort to find out why I was unhappy with my experience. She turned her attention back to the other party that entered the restaurant and proceeded to regale them with her stories. My friend, who witnessed the exchange, was appalled by her response. Rather than cause a scene, I decided to leave. I was already disgusted by the careless lack of cleanliness. I was even more turned off by how I was treated by the staff and the owner. While I understand that things happen, how you handle the situation speaks volumes. I got the message about this place loud and clear about the value they place on offering a clean and quality dining experience. Though it has received a lot of reviews for the food, I can't confirm or deny the quality of the food, but I can tell you that the service is of very poor quality. Something to think about if you're considering dining here.

title: Creole Orleans
text:
This hidden gem is a must try!! The staff are very friendly and will be helpful if you need assistance navigating through all of the delicious options on the menu. The food is AMAZING! Literally everything is filled with flavor. The jerk turkey wings are my favorite with the perfectly cooked and seasoned rice and peas. All of the veggies are great. Not your typical spot where the protein is usually the star of the show and the sides are mediocre. Here, you get flavor in every single dish. You can‚Äôt go wrong with the greens, cabbage, green beans, &/or broccoli. The creole spaghetti is a hit too! The manager/owner of the spot was also kind enough to let me try the rasta pasta on the house recently and it was also delicious. You really can‚Äôt go wrong with anything on the menu here‚Ä¶. And they are consistent! Ive eaten here many times and the flavors and great portions are sheets the same.
My only knock on this place is the location (inside the Greenbriar Mall) because I know they would be even more booming in a better location! This is a spot that truly deserves community support and I hope to see them outgrow the mall. In the meantime, they are still totally worth the trip inside (conveniently located near the food court entrance)!

title: Eats
text: Affordable and classic. Simple and delicious. We decided to take our 19 year old to an Atlanta staple, since she is going to college here now. The jerk chicken was fantastic, falling off the bone. The meatloaf was delicious and sweet, The chili was seasoned perfectly and the cornbread was as perfect as classic cornbread can be. Next time you're hungry, try EATS!

title: Farm Burger
text: Very good burgers and fries. Very nice atmosphere and friendly staff. Good prices for the quality of the food. Burgers were very fresh and tasty French fries were also very well cooked nice texture and crunch to them.

title: Farm Burger
text: Very cool, trendy burger joint in Midtown Atlanta. Had the farm burger with fries. Was very good. Service was great. They ask how you want your burger cooked and it came out fast. Definitely recommend.

title: Farm Burger
text:
The food that I had today was not impressive at all. Some of the sweet potato fries were overcooked, the burger itself had no flavor which was rather odd, and the person that took my order behaved as if he didn't care when I was speaking to him. I appreciate you talking to me about it, but don't walk away when I'm still talking or interrupt me. The gentleman Ian knows a thing or two about service. Unless he's there, I will not come back nor and waste my time trying to support this business.

I'm not planning on coming back unless you all make sure the food is consistently delicious and the service is equally up to par. This is my second time coming here. I'm not sure if the rain is the cause or if you are short staffed or if it is a personal vendetta. There was hardly anyone in there - maybe 6 other people.

Also, the cookie that you sell are also shoddy as well. There's barely any flavor, it is far too thin and crumbly, and the price is egregious!

Step ya game up Farm Burger otherwise you'll be out of business in no time!
